### Describe the bug
If I put an `<InputRadio>` inside a wrapper element, and add an event handler to the wrapper, interactions with the radio input break. For example, a click handler breaks clicking, a keyboard handler breaks keyboard input, etc.

I've only had the issue with radio inputs. `<InputCheckbox>`, `<InputText>`, etc. seem to be unaffected. If I remove the handler, the radio works as expected.

### To Reproduce
Here's a simple way to reproduce the problem.

```C#
@page "/eventbug"

<div @onclick="OnClick">
    <EditForm Model="@model">
        <p>
            <InputRadioGroup @bind-Value="model.Size">
                Size:
                @foreach (var size in (Size[])Enum.GetValues(typeof(Size)))
                {
                    <br />
                    <label>
                        <InputRadio Value="size" />
                        @size
                    </label>
                }
            </InputRadioGroup>
        </p>

        <p>
            <label>
                Enabled:
                <InputCheckbox @bind-Value="model.Enabled" />
            </label>
        </p>
    </EditForm>

    <p>Clicks: @clicks</p>
</div>

@code {
    public enum Size { Small, Medium, Large }

    public class TestModel
    {
        public Size Size { get; set; }
        public bool Enabled { get; set; }
    }

    private TestModel model = new TestModel();

    private int clicks;

    void OnClick(MouseEventArgs e)
    {
        clicks++;
    }
}
```

### Exceptions (if any)
None.

### Further technical details
- ASP.NET Core version: 5.0.1

I'm testing some endpoints in a .Net Core 3.1 ApiController that have [Authorize] attributes assigned.  In the tests, when I try to access a GET method with an account that does not have the proper credentials, I'm getting a 403 Forbidden response.  When I access a POST or PUT method with the same account, I'm receiving a 400 Bad Request response.  I would expect the response to be the same for all methods.  When running the application, I'm seeing the proper response; it's only when using the TestServer that I see the incorrect response.

